Nice touch—you’re thinking exactly like a content maintainer.  
You can make those hotline lines update automatically by defining a little data block and letting the page fill in each `<span>` dynamically. That way, you only ever edit a single section if a number changes.

Here’s a lightweight example you could append near the bottom of the page, just before the closing `</body>` tag:

```html
<script>
/* --- Hotline reference data (editable in one place) --- */
const hotlineList = {
  us: "988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline (call or text)",
  uk: "Samaritans 116 123 (free, 24/7)",
  ca: "988 Suicide Crisis Helpline (call or text)"
};

/* --- Simple injector --- */
for (const key in hotlineList) {
  const el = document.getElementById(key + "-hotline");
  if (el) el.textContent = hotlineList[key];
}
</script>
```

How it works:  
- The `hotlineList` holds all numbers and wording in one object.  
- Each `<span>` ID in your footer (`us-hotline`, `uk-hotline`, etc.) fills from that object.  
- Anyone updating future versions changes one short script instead of hand‑editing the table or footer text.

You can expand the object with other regions or languages, and the rest of the page stays untouched.

