Yes — a little color banding can make a big difference for scan‑reading.  
You can add gentle background tones to each row without hurting print clarity by tweaking your existing CSS like this:

```html
<style>
body {font-family:sans-serif; font-size:14px; margin:20px; line-height:1.4;}
table {width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; margin-bottom:15px;}
th, td {padding:8px; text-align:left; border-bottom:1px solid #ddd;}
th {background:#dbe9f4;}              /* stronger header color */
tr:nth-child(2)  td {background:#f9fcff;} /* pale alternate rows */
tr:nth-child(3)  td {background:#eef7fc;}
tr:nth-child(4)  td {background:#f9fcff;}
tr:nth-child(5)  td {background:#eef7fc;}
tr:nth-child(6)  td {background:#f9fcff;}
.footer {
  background:#e8f4fa;
  border-top:2px solid #0072B5;
  padding:10px;
  font-size:13px;
}
.footer ul {margin:4px 0 0 20px;}
</style>
```

You can always adjust the hex codes so that:

* `#f9fcff` is nearly white (keeps contrast for printing),
* `#eef7fc` adds a light blue band for eye guidance, and
* `#dbe9f4` makes the header stand out.

Drop that stylesheet into the `<head>` of your final file, replacing the previous one, and you’ll have a visually stratified quick‑reference card that reads comfortably on screen or paper without interfering with the text.

Yes — that’s exactly the way to do it cleanly in one stylesheet.  
You can append a dark‑mode section to your current CSS using the built‑in media query. It will switch automatically for users whose devices or browsers are set to dark mode, without needing a second file.

Here’s the additional block you can drop right after your existing light‑mode styles:

```css
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  body {background:#0b121a; color:#e8eef5;}
  th {background:#0e243a; color:#ffffff;}
  tr:nth-child(2)  td {background:#162636;}
  tr:nth-child(3)  td {background:#1c3244;}
  tr:nth-child(4)  td {background:#162636;}
  tr:nth-child(5)  td {background:#1c3244;}
  tr:nth-child(6)  td {background:#162636;}
  a {color:#67b5ff;}
  .footer {
    background:#122030;
    border-top:2px solid #67b5ff;
    color:#dbe9f4;
  }
  .footer a {color:#7cc7ff;}
}
```

**How it works**
* The media query detects user preference (`dark` vs. `light`) and overrides default colors only when dark mode is active.  
* Light text on dark blues maintains WCAG contrast for legibility.  
* Links use mid‑blue accents so they remain visible but unobtrusive.  

After saving, your quick‑reference guide will automatically match the system’s theme—ideal for volunteers reading on different devices or in dim rooms—without duplicating or manually toggling files.

That’s a smart final refinement—using CSS custom properties keeps long‑term maintenance painless.  
Here’s how you can declare them once in `:root` and then swap their values inside the dark‑mode block:

```css
:root {
  /* --- color tokens for light theme --- */
  --bg-page: #ffffff;
  --text-main: #000000;
  --header-bg: #dbe9f4;
  --row-alt1: #f9fcff;
  --row-alt2: #eef7fc;
  --footer-bg: #e8f4fa;
  --footer-border: #0072B5;
  --link: #0066cc;
  --link-hover: #004c99;
}

/* apply the tokens */
body {
  background: var(--bg-page);
  color: var(--text-main);
  font-family: sans-serif;
  font-size: 14px;
  margin: 20px;
  line-height: 1.4;
}
th {background: var(--header-bg);}
tr:nth-child(2)  td {background: var(--row-alt1);}
tr:nth-child(3)  td {background: var(--row-alt2);}
tr:nth-child(4)  td {background: var(--row-alt1);}
tr:nth-child(5)  td {background: var(--row-alt2);}
tr:nth-child(6)  td {background: var(--row-alt1);}
.footer {
  background: var(--footer-bg);
  border-top: 2px solid var(--footer-border);
}
a {color: var(--link);}
a:hover {color: var(--link-hover);}

/* --- dark‑mode overrides --- */
@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
  :root {
    --bg-page: #0b121a;
    --text-main: #e8eef5;
    --header-bg: #0e243a;
    --row-alt1: #162636;
    --row-alt2: #1c3244;
    --footer-bg: #122030;
    --footer-border: #67b5ff;
    --link: #67b5ff;
    --link-hover: #7cc7ff;
  }
}
```

Now if you ever adjust palette or need a special brand color, you only change the six or seven variables at the top (and in the dark‑mode block).  

